<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=200 valign=top align=left>
<a href="leb_2.html"><img src="leb_2_sm.jpg" width=200 height=393
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 border=0 alt=""></a><p></td>

<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=350 ALIGN=left><img src="rvllogo.gif" width=269 height=36
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 border=0 alt=""><p>
<a href="lebeaupin1.html"><img src="lebeaupin1_sm.jpg" width=128 height=213
align=left vspace=6 hspace=0 border=0></a><font face="arial, helvetica" color="#318E6E" size=2><b>
the encountering of fantasy is what intrests me most in photography. my quest is of a sensuous, even sensual nature, an not an artistic one. through my photography i nourish no other hope than to rouse the pleasure of looking. i am self-taught. my photography is introspective.
<p>
the emotion of an encouner derives as much from the circumstances in which it emerges as from the actual personality of the other party. likewise, the physical qualities of the model are important in the narrative process; but if they are to become more than a purely anatomical testimony, setting them up in the right way is prerequisite.
<p>
studio photography often reveals a body <img src="leb.jpg" width=120 height=194
align=right vspace=3 hspace=0 border=0>devoid of an identity of history and, consequently, not immersed in the real subsance of life. outdoor photography ‘cruises the image’ and is a fantasy of everyday life adorning and giving substance to the person within. the model ceases to be a part of a photographic game and becomes a gesture to real life.<br>
<p align=right>
—rv lebeaupin</td></TABLE>
