<img src="sealpotential.gif" width=163 height=44
align=bottom vspace=3 hspace=0 border=0 alt=""><br>
<font face="arial, helvetica" size=2><font color="#4D8B7E"><b>
the minimum requirements for entering the u.s. navy’s elite seal training program consist of the ability to swim 500 yards in 12:30 using the breast stroke, run 1.5 miles in 11:30 wearing boots, pass basic calisthenics tests including 42 push-ups within two minutes and be in excellent physical health.  
<br><br>
by the end of training, seals will be expected to run 14 miles, swim 5.5 miles, and do 180 push ups. in the eighth week of training seal applicants go  through hell week. about half the seal applicants drop out of the program during these excruciating five an one-half days. 
<br><br>
an average day in hell week might start with a 6 am breakfast followed by a four mile run down the beach with a 150-pound boat on your head. a late-morning bout with the obstacle course could be followed by calisthenics in 60° water. 
<br><br>
you might spend the afternoon crashing a boat into rock walls or swim two miles though pounding surf. with evening, a game of hide and seek with stinging pellet cartridges might be in store. finally, a midnight supper and another four-mile run down the beach. just another day. interested? 
<p>

<img src="seal5.jpg" width=110 height=98 align=left vspace=0 hspace=0 border=0 alt="">
<font color="#A7A16D">recruiter<br>
naval special<br> 
warfare center<br>
2446 trident way<br>
san diego, california 92115
<br></td></TABLE>

