<html>
<META Name="keywords" Content="Eadweard Muybridge new media pioneers motion pictures pacific interactive media zoopraxiscope">
<head>
<title>New Media Pioneers · EADWEARD MUYBRIDGE · How Muybridge Did It...</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#000000" text="#9AC5D1" link="#74A991" vlink="#74A991">
<embed src="muy_3.mid" autostart=true loop=false hidden=true>
<br><br>
<center>
<img src="champion.gif" align=bottom hspace=0 vspace=0 border=0 width=475 height=74><br>

<TABLE WIDTH=500 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=21>
<TD valign=top width=123 align=right>
<img src="boxer.gif" align=bottom hspace=0 vspace=6 border=1 width=123 height=133><br>
<font face="arial, helvetica" size=2 color="#6DAD9C"><b>At the University of Pennsylvania in 1884-5, Muybridge  photographed studies of people including the fighter seen shadow boxing here. His subjects included athletes, professors, even amputees.<br><br>

Up to a thousand negatives might be shot each day, and Muybridge captured more than 100,000 images during his Pennsylvania days.<br><br>

The $30,000 invested in the project by the University was an enormous sum, but it produced a huge volume of work. The results, <i>The Human Figure in Motion.</i> Check your local library.</b></td>


<TD valign=bottom align=left><font color="#CE8E71">
<font face="times new roman, times" size=5 color="#6DAD9C"><b><i>How Muybridge Did It . . .</i>
<br><spacer type=vertical size=6>
<font face="arial, helvetica" size=2 color="#9AC5D1"><b>Muybridge erected a stage, 120 feet long, marked off in a grid pattern so that the slightest change in human muscle movement could be easily analyzed. The small squares are 5 centimeters across, the larger blocks, 10 centimeters.<br><br>

The cameras, 12 of them, were about 50 feet away, placed close together — about 6 inches apart. Through a complex and ingenious triggering system using a tuning fork as a clock, Muybridge was able to fire the cameras with precision, at a frequency of 1/60th of a second to several seconds.<br><br>

With three batteries of cameras, Muybridge could capture simultaneous action from different angles — the precursor of today’s multi-camera shoot. Did this make Muybridge the first motion picture director? There’s lively debate about that, but little doubt that his work stands alone.<br><br>

His glass negatives were 4 by 5 inches in size and Muybridge made prints as large as 9 by 12 inches which he sold in sets of 781 for around $500, a pricey sum in 1885.</b><br><br>
<center>
<TABLE WIDTH=210 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD valign=top width=68 align=center>
<img src="bucket_blue.gif" align=left hspace=0 vspace=0 border=0 width=68 height=185></td>
<TD valign=top width=68 align=center>
<img src="bucket_red.gif" align=left hspace=0 vspace=0 border=0 width=68 height=185></td>
<TD valign=top width=68 align=center>
<img src="bucket_green.gif" align=left hspace=0 vspace=0 border=0 width=68 height=185></TD></table>

<p>
<img src="contrl04.gif" USEMAP="#index" align=bottom hspace=0 vspace=0 border=0 width=100 height=27></center>
</TD></table>
<br>


<br>
</center>
</blockquote>
