<html>
<META Name="keywords" Content="Eadweard Muybridge new media pioneers motion pictures pacific interactive media zoopraxiscope">
<head>
<title>New Media Pioneers · EADWEARD MUYBRIDGE · Horse Flies!</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#000000" text="#CEB37E" link="#74A991" vlink="#74A991">
<embed src="muy_2.mid" autostart=true loop=false hidden=true>

<center>
<br><br>
<img src="flies.gif" align=bottom hspace=0 vspace=0 border=0 width=475 height=73><br>
<br>
<TABLE WIDTH=500 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=10>
<TD WIDTH=292 valign=top align=right><font color="#CE8E71">
<img src="horse.gif" hspace=0 vspace=03align=bottom border=1 width=271 height=145>
<br><br>

<font face="times new roman, times" size=5 color="#AD9484"><b><i>Muybridge in America</i>
<br><spacer type=vertical size=6>
<font face="arial, helvetica" size=2 color="#BABDA2"><b>In the 1850s, Muybridge traveled to San Francisco where he established himself as an innovative photographer, pioneering — among other things — panoramic photographs of the Bay Area skyline.  
<br><br>

In Palo Alto, California in 1877, under the sponsorship of former California governor and horse breeder Leland Stanford,  Muybridge set to work settling an old arguement among sportsmen. Did all four hooves of a galloping horse leave the ground for an instant?<br><br>

With a $40,000 grant from Stanford, Muybridge set up multiple cameras tripped by strings and rubber bands, capable of capturing a horse at full run. The result was an international sensation, launching Muybridge on a European speaking tour and earning him a place in the history of photography. And, the movies’ first lawsuit — a squabble with Stanford over who should get credit for the idea.
<br><br>
<img src="contrl04.gif" USEMAP="#index" align=bottom hspace=0 vspace=0 border=0 width=100 height=27></TD>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<img src="bedtime.gif" align=left hspace=7 vspace=3 border=1 width=75 height=151> 
<font face="arial, helvetica" size=2 color="#89A1A2"><b>
Muybridge was able to project his sequential glass plates by mounting them on a circular disc placed between a calcium carbide ‘limelight’ and a lens. He called the device the Zoopraxiscope.
<br><br>

Astonished audiences witnessed the illusion of moving pictures. The action looped over and over again, just as it does here. 
<br><br>
It was the birth of motion pictures, and of a series of movement studies, <i>The Horse in Motion.</i>
<br>
<hr size=1><font face="times new roman, times" size=5 color="#AD9484"><b><i>The press said...</i>
<font face="arial, helvetica" size=2 color="#BABDA2"><br>‘Mr. Muybridge has laid the foundation of a new way of entertaining people and we predict that his magic lantern will make the round of the civilized world.’<br><font face="arial, helvetica" size=2 color="#AD9484"> —Alta California, May 5, 1880</b></td>
</table>

</center>
</blockquote>
</body>
