<TD VALIGN=middle WIDTH=180 ALIGN=left>
<font face="arial, helvetica" color="#896642"><p><font size=2><b>
intoxicated with victory and testosterone, the varsity football team returns triumphant to the locker room.
<br><br>
they’ve been tackling guyz all afternoon, working up a juicy sweat.
<br><br>
now comes the shower scene, towel-snapping, checking out equipment. sorry, that was then. this is now.
<br><br>
‘i can’t remember the last time i saw a kid take a shower,’ says dan miller, veteran athletic director at anaheim high school in a recent interview with the <u>los angeles times</u>.
<br><br>
san fernando high school english teacher and football coach robert garcia attributes the aversion to showers to both modesty and the towel shortage. ‘maybe 10% out of a p.e. class of 50 kids take showers. 
<br><br>
the main reason is a lot of schools don’t have the budget for laundering towels. most of them go in and wet their t-shirt and wipe under their arms so that by the fifth period they are hummin’ [with body odor].’
<br><br>
tony chretin, varsity football coach at venice high school, says that shower-phobia isn’t new. ‘in the last 10 years, almost no one showers. embarrassment is part of it. our football guys go in there with their girdles and pads on to shower. most of them just put on deodorant and go to their parties.’
<br><br>
brent ellis, a sophomore at westminster high school, is goalie for the varsity water polo team. he and his teammates are exceptions. they actually shower. but not in the nude. 
<br><br>
‘all the guys i know shower in swimsuits,’ ellis says. ‘i have never seen anyone shower at school in the nude.’</td>
