<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia">


<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="B80000" link="B80000" vlink="B80000">

<p><br><br>
<center>
<TABLE WIDTH=525 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=381 ALIGN=left VALIGN=bottom>
<img src="rubblekid.jpg" width=381 height=200
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="photo by JIM BARTLETT">
<p>
<font color="#525D60" face="arial, helvetica" size=2><b> <a href="/index.html">Pacific Interactive Media Corp</a> </b>presents<p>
<font color="B80000" size=7><b>
<tt>Berserkistan</tt></b><br>
<font color="#525D60" face="arial, helvetica" size=3><b>
The most successful pilot ever<br>
produced in Internet journalism</b><p>

<font color="#525D60" face="arial, helvetica" size=2> 
Pacific Interactive Media Corp. published Berserkistan in Bosnia as a daily from January to August, 1966. 

<p>
<IMG WIDTH=98 HEIGHT=123 BORDER=0 SRC="journal_top.gif" VSPACE=3 ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Jim Bartlett’s Bosnia Journal">
Editor-in-Chief Jim Bartlett, a veteran photojournalist covering Bosnia since 1992, reported on the arrival of NATO troops, introduced readers to real people living in a nation torn by 3½ years of war, and broke dozens of original stories. Berserkistan was accessed by readers in 33 countries and scored up to 130,000 hits a day.

<p>
Bartlett became the first reporter in history to cover a war zone exclusively for the Internet. He shot his own photos, wrote extraordinary stories, and filed them at Berserkistan using America Online’s Zagreb dial-up port.

<p>
In its 8 months of daily coverage, Berserkistan grew to include the Pulitzer-nominated photography of Johnathan Thornton, the war diaries of Steve Gaunt and an extraordinary example of the humanitarian possibilities of Internet journalism by documentary filmmaker Cynthia Lee.

<p>
<IMG WIDTH=135 HEIGHT=127 BORDER=0 SRC="elvis.jpg" VSPACE=3 ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Elvis Muhic">
Lee reported the story of Elvis Muhic, an 11-year-old Bosnian boy whose legs had been shattered by the weapons of war. Berserkistan’s pleas for help triggered a worldwide campaign to help the boy walk again. Elvis Muhic is now in Danville, Pennsylvania, receiving the surgery and medical he could not receive at home.

<p>
Other Berserkistan achievements included . . .<br>
<ul>
<li>Up to 15 news stories daily. Items rarely covered in other Internet sites or newspapers anywhere.
<li>More daily news from Bosnia than all the other news sites on the Web combined.
<li>Live coverage of the death of U.S. Commerce Secretary Ron Brown in Croatia. 
<li>Ongoing coverage of the War Crimes Tribunal.
<li>Berserkistan was covered in <a href="/berserk/wired.html"><i>Wired</i></a> and won scores of <a href="/berserk/kudos.html">awards</a> for its work.
</ul>
<p>
Berserkistan changed the face of journalism on the Web — from CNN to the Electronic Telegraph. As <i>The Boston Globe</i> reported, "Berserkistan is simply the best original journalism ever seen on the Net." 
<p>
Now, Berserkistan is preparing its expansion into other major news stories including the devastation of the world’s rainforests with live video coverage and global video teleconferencing.
<p>
<b><a href="/berserk/berserk.html">Visit Berserkistan</a>

  
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=150 ALIGN=right VALIGN=middle>
</td>
</TABLE>
</center>
<BODY>



</MAP>
</HTML>
