<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: CIA Worries About Islamic Militants in Bosnia</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
After Saudi Blast, CIA<br>
Worries About Islamic<br>
Militants in Bosnia</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<b>By Kurt Schork</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="deutch.gif" width=157 height=197
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="John Deutch" align=left border=0>
SARAJEVO, July 8 (Reuter) - America's CIA Director John Deutch slipped into Sarajevo last week on a visit revealing Washington fears that Islamic militants in Bosnia are a threat to U.S. forces here, diplomats said on Monday. The unannounced trip came soon after a bomb blast tore through a Saudi Arabian military complex housing foreigners, killing 19 Americans and injuring more than 250 people.
<p>
Several thousand Islamic soldiers fought for the Moslem-led government side during Bosnia's 43-month war but all were supposed to leave under the Dayton peace agreement signed in December last year. The U.S. worries that some remain as a threat to Americans, in violation of the Dayton accord.
<p>
"Given the recent attack in Saudi Arabia any Western nation operating in Bosnia, but especially the United States, must evaluate the threat to its troops from terrorists," a Western diplomat who asked not to be named said on Monday. "We know some Arabs and Iranians who were here during the war remain in Bosnia and that some carry a grudge against the West. A few determined people can create havoc. Word is that Deutch was here to share his concerns with the government."
<p>
The havoc caused by a June 25 truck-bomb attack on American service personnel in Saudi Arabia prompted a review of U.S. military security around the world. The United States recently certified that the Dayton banagainst "foreign forces" had been met, at least sufficiently to make Bosnia eligible for a major U.S.-sponsored military assistance programme. But NATO, which leads a 50,000-strong peace implementation force in Bosnia including about 18,000 U.S. soldiers, reports that as many as several hundred militants from Iran and other Islamic nations still remain in Bosnia.
<p>
"There is general compliance with Dayton on the matter of "foreign forces," Lieutenant-Colonel Max Mariner, a NATO spokesman, told Reuters on Monday.

</td>
</table>


<br><br>
