<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Perry Hopes to Accelerate US Arms Deal</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
In Sarajevo, Perry Hopes to<br>
Accelerate US Arms Deal</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<b>By Robert Kearns</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="perry_73.gif" width=262 height=217 align=left 
vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry">
SARAJEVO, July 3 (Reuter) - U.S. Defence Secretary William Perry hopes feuding Bosnian Croats and Moslems can quickly break a logjam over powersharing and so unleash a flood of American weapons into the country, U.S. officials said Wednesday. Perry, who arrived in Sarajevo on Wednesday as part of a European tour, wants to conclude a deal allowing the shipment of $100 million worth of tanks, guns, ammunition and equipment.
<p>
The United States believes the weaponry would give Bosnia's uneasy federation of Croats and Moslems enough military muscle to match Bosnia's Serbs. "We hope we can come close to finalising it," said a U.S. official travelling with Perry. "We just don't see how they can survive as separate...it's pivotal," said the official, who asked not be named.
<p>
Perry was meeting Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic, leaders of Bosnia's military and key members of the coalition government to hammer out a deal that would define how the Croats and Moslems would share power over the military. The two sides must agree to a new defence law that would require approval of Bosnia's parliament.
<p>
The arms flow from the United States, which refused throughout the 43-month war to send weapons to the outgunned
Moslems, has been bottled up because of the unwillingness of the two to settle on what level of the military would operate under joint command and what would remain Croat or Moslem controlled.
<p>
The United States has enlisted four Moslem countries to help train and equip Bosnia: Turkey, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates.
<p>
The United States plans to provide the Bosnian army with 45 M-60 tanks, far superior to the ageing Soviet-era tanks used by Bosnia's Serbs, some of which are over 50 years old and have now been secured in barn yards and at factory sites under the terms of the U.S.-brokered Dayton peace accord.
<p>
Bosnia would also get 46,000 M-16 automatic weapons, machine guns, 113 armoured personnel carriers, 15 helicopters and 840 anti-tank weapons. It would also get communications equipment. Perry plans to spend July 4, American Independence Day, with U.S. troops in Bosnia. The United States has about 18,000 troops on the ground in Bosnia and is the largest contributor to the NATO-led peace force in the country.</td>
</table>


