<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Bosnian Muslim-Croat Army James Pardew MPRI Alija Izetbegovic Kresimir Zubak">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: US Company to Begin Training Bosnian Muslim-Croat Army</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=5><b>
US Company to Begin Training<br>
Bosnian Muslim-Croat Army</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="army_66.gif" width=262 height=0216 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Bosnian Army Soldiers" align=left border=0>
SARAJEVO, July 7 (AP) -- Bosnia’s Muslims and Croats have agreed on the text of a defense law that would allow an American company to start training their joint army. <p>
A newspaper said Sunday the company is ready to start work within 30 days. The law, to be presented to the Bosnian parliament this week, establishes a single interim defense ministry and a joint military command for the shaky Bosnian-Croat federation that governs half of Bosnia.
<p>
The joint structures are to exist for three months, until elections are held in September and permanent institutions are then developed. Negotiations on the law dragged on for almost four months. The main sticking point was the command structure of Bosnia’s future joint Muslim-Croat army.
<p>
Ambassador James Pardew, the U.S. envoy for military stability in the Balkans, says the law effectively leaves leaders from both groups in charge -- Alija Izetbegovic, the president of Bosnia-Herzegovina, and a Muslim; and Kresimir Zubak, a Croat and the president of the Muslim-Croat Federation.
<p>
Passage of the law is the key condition for start-up of the U.S.-sponsored military training and equipment program. The Bosnian government negotiated with several contractors before choosing Military Professional Resources Inc., a northern Virginia-based consulting firm made up of recently retired, high-ranking U.S. military officials, including the former head of the Defense Intelligence Agency. MPRI is credited with helping retrain the Croatian army, which retook a large chunk of its territory from Croatian Serb insurgents in a lightning strike last summer.
<p>
MPRI representatives are ready to come to Sarajevo and sign the contract, the Oslobodjenje daily said, and their instructors are due to arrive within 30 days to start training.
</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
