Military Professional Resources, Inc Train-and-Equip Bosnian army">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: US Train-and-Equip Program Begins in Bosnia</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
US Train-and-Equip<br>
Program Begins in Bosnia</b>
<font size=3>
<p>
<b>
Training by Virginia’s Military Professional Resources 
is to be funded out of $140 million pledged by 
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Malaysia, and Brunei</b>
<p><br>
<font size=2>
<img src="army_66.gif" width=262 height=0216 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Bosnian Army Soldiers" align=left border=0>
SARAJEVO, July 15 (AP) -- Retired U.S. military officers arrived Sunday to launch a training program for Bosnian forces under Washington’s plans to build up the Bosnian military. 
<p>
The United States also has pledged to help equip the Muslim-Croat federation army, transferring $100 million in military equipment to Bosnia in the near future. 
<p>
Training by Virginia-based Military Professional Resources, Inc., is to be funded out of $140 million pledged by Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Malaysia, and Brunei for both equipment and training. Turkey already is providing some training to government soldiers, and is expected to transfer some equipment. The training program will be carried out by 163 former U.S. military personnel under retired Maj. Gen. William M. Boice, who arrived Sunday.
<p>
The American equipment being sent includes more than 46,000 rifles, a thousand machine guns, almost 6,600 radios and tactical telephones, 45 tanks, 80 armored personnel carriers, 840 light anti-tank weapons and 15 utility helicopters, according to the White House.
A Bosnian Defense Ministry official, however, criticized the age and quality of weaponry.
<p>
"Everybody now wants to get rid of their old equipment by dumping it in Bosnia," he said Sunday, speaking on condition of anonymity.
<p>
The official said the radio equipment was from the 1960s or 1970s and the tanks were too old, adding the weapons would not create a balance of power with Serbs, the main goal of the program. U.S. officials said M-60 tanks were on offer. But the government wanted more modern Abrams tanks.
</td>
</table>


