Bosnian Serbs threats International Police Task Force IPTF Ugljevik mayor Miladin Stefanovic">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Bosnian Serbs Threaten to Capture, Kill UN Police</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Bosnian Serbs Threaten to <br>
Capture, Kill UN Police</b>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=3><b>
‘We believe that the Republika Srpska authorities should publicly condemn this outrageous threat and we believe that something should be done about it.’</b><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
—IPTF Spokesman Alex Ivanko
<p>
<font size=2>
SARAJEVO, July 18 (Reuter) - Bosnian Serbs have threatened to capture and kill United Nations police monitors if their leader Radovan Karadzic is arrested on war crimes charges, a U.N. official said on Thursday. The threat drew an immediate reponse from the NATO-led peace Implementation Force (IFOR) which said it would protect the International Police Task Force (IPTF).
<p>
IPTF spokesman Alex Ivanko told a news conference that the threat had been issued by the Serb mayor of the northern Bosnian town of Ugljevik. Bosnian Serbs also issued threats earlier this week against IFOR and the IPTF if Western forces tried to arrest Serb leaders wanted by the U.N. war crimes tribunal.
<p>
"Mayor Miladin Stefanovic, in conversation with U.N. civil affairs officials... stated that if Karadzic is arrested, the Republika Srpska (Bosnian Serb Republic) will respond with military action targeting IFOR and all U.N. IPTF monitors," Ivanko said. 
<p>
He quoted Stefanovic as saying Bosnian Serbs would not repeat an earlier "mistake" of trusting Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic who ordered them to release U.N. hostages seized in May, 1995 during the war. "According to (Stefanovic), this time all U.N. police monitors will be captured and killed immediately," Ivanko said.
<p>
"We believe this is a very explicit threat," he said. "We believe that the Republika Srpska authorities should publicly condemn this outrageous threat and we believe that something should be done about it."
<p>
IFOR spokesman Major Brett Boudreau, said: "There's no doubt that IFOR will move very strongly and robustly to assist the IPTF in the event of an incident of that nature." Boudreau added: "We stand by the IPTF on this 100 percent. We will not be intimidated."</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<img src="background.gif" alt="To learn more..." align=bottom border=0><br>
Berserkistan, July 16 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="karadzic_716a.html">Serbs in Doboj Threaten to take UN Police Hostage</a><br>
Berserkistan, July 16 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="holbrooke_716a.html">Holbrooke Pulls No Punches Responding to Serb Threats</a>
<p>
INTERNATIONAL POLICE TASK FORCE<br>
<a href="http://www.vm.ee/nato/ifor/afsouth/t960716a.htm">Transcript of the Press Briefing</a> IFOR, 16 July 1996<br>
<a href="http://dosfan.lib.uic.edu/www/current/bosnia/bosnia_police_force.html">Implementing the Dayton Peace Agreement</a> International Police Task Force<br>


