<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia Radovan Karadzic Ratko Mladic Alija Izetbegovic NATO IFOR Balkan Richard Holbrooke elections boycott">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Izetbegovic Warns Holbrooke of Bosnian Election Boycott</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Izetbegovic Warns<br> 
Holbrooke of Bosnian<br> 
Election Boycott</b>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=3><b>
‘We have demanded that Karadzic be removed from public 
office, including the post of president of the SDS’</b><br>
<font size=2>—Alija Izetbegovic, President of Bosnia and Herzegovina
<p>
<b>By Mark Heinrich</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="izet_solo.gif" width=200 height=265
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Alija Izetbegovic" align=left border=0>
SARAJEVO, July 16 (Reuter) Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic warned visiting U.S. peacemaker Richard Holbrooke on Tuesday that Moslems might boycott postwar elections if indicted Serb war criminals are allowed to take part.<p>
Holbrooke, architect of the 1995 Dayton peace treaty for Bosnia, returned to the region on Monday to rescue flagging international efforts to remove separatist Serb leader Radovan Karadzic from political life.
<p>
The focus of Holbrooke's mission was to lean on President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia, the Bosnian Serbs' patron, to depose Karadzic while the West debates how best to arrest him for trial before a U.N. war crimes tribunal. Izetbegovic said that while NATO peace troops had separated Bosnia's ethnic armies admirably, many civilian aspects of the Dayton accord had not been implemented.
<p>
"Most important is that war criminals are still present in politics. This was the key issue of today's talks (with Holbrooke)," Izetbegovic said with Holbrooke alongside. "We have demanded that Karadzic be removed from public office, including the post of president of the SDS (party). I've conveyed the message to Mr Holbrooke that if the SDS under Karadzic's leadership takes part in the elections, then there could be a boycott of the elections by our side," the Moslem president said.
<p><img src="election_sm_sm_r.gif" width=100 height=122
vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="Bosnia's Election" align=right border=0>
<b>Under the Dayton treaty, the September 14 elections</b> are designed to create federal governing institutions reintegrating Serb, Moslem and Croat-dominated areas of Bosnia. But Karadzic and his ultra-nationalist Serb Democratic Party regard the balloting as the seal on an independent state carved out by conquest and expulsions of Moslems and Croats.
<p>
Western leaders believe the only chance of moderating SDS policies, averting a ruinous Moslem boycott and holding credible elections is to knock Karadzic off the political map. Holbrooke, whose aggressive, indefatigable diplomacy achieved peace in Bosnia after years of failed U.N. mediation, said he saw "signs of rebirth, revitalisation and rebuilding" all over Bosnia since Dayton's signing.
<p>
"But it is true, as President Izetbegovic just said, that a small group of people continue to thwart the political aspects of the Dayton agreements," he said.
<p>
Holbrooke said he would have talks with Milosevic in Belgrade on Wednesday and President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia, patron of nationalist Bosnian Croats who also oppose reunification of Bosnia, on Wednesday night. "I will make it clear (we are) insisting on full compliance with Dayton. The activities of the Serb leaders of Pale (capital of the Bosnian Serb republic) are incompatible with full compliance."</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<img src="background.gif" alt="To learn more..." align=bottom border=0><br>
