Radovan Karadzic elections Hasan Muratovic Biljana Plavsic
Robert Frowick Aleksa Buha">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Election Delay: Where the Players Stand</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Bosnian Election Delay:<br>
Where the Players Stand</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<b>From wire service reports</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="election_sm.gif" width=100 height=143 hspace=0 vspace=0 align=left border=0 alt="The Bosnian Elections">
SARAJEVO, July 14 - On Sunday, the OSCE put the brakes on Bosnia's election campaign, urging Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic to use the time in order to step down from office. The campaign was scheduled to start Monday, but the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said it would now start July 19. The reason for the four-day delay, the organization’s spokeswoman Johanna van Vliet said, was "to offer the opportunity for Karadzic to step down for the sake of the Serbian people."
<p>
Here is a synopsis of the positions of the key players.
<p>

<p>
<p>
<img src="muratovic_90.gif" width=102 height=115 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Hasan Muratovic" align=left border=0>
<b>Hasan Muratovic</b> did not expressly warn of a Bosnian Moslem pullout from the September 14 elections. Such a step would anger Western powers who are determined to stage the vote even if flawed and control the purse strings of reconstruction aid for Bosnia. His words served notice that a vote meant by Dayton to reintegrate Bosnia would be discredited in Moslem eyes if Karadzic, an ultra-separatist who only nominally accepted the treaty terms, retained supremacy over half the country. Analysts fear the ballot could ratify Bosnia's partition anyway because ethnic nationalist parties dominate Moslem, Serb and Croat power centres in the former Yugoslav republic. "I think it is beyond the dignity of the Bosnian people to vote in the presence of elections including the Serb entity," Bosnian Prime Minister Hasan Muratovic told Reuters.
<p>
<img src="plavsic_90.gif" width=102 height=115 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Biljana Plavsic" align=left border=0>
<b>Biljana Plavsic</b>, the hardline vice president to whom Karadzic delegated his functions, said at the weekend that the Bosnian Serbs would not deviate from their crusade to ratify the "statehood" of their entity, the Serb Republic. "A divided Bosnia is a reality that must be accepted," she said in an interview with a Serbian newspaper. Plavsic met with Robert Frowick on Thursday and her party was urged by the diplomat to participate in the elections. 
<p>
<img src="frowick_90.gif" width=102 height=115 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Robert Frowick" align=left border=0>
<b>Robert Frowick</b>, head of the Bosnia office of the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe which is arranging the elections, has threatened to disqualify the Serb Democratic Party (SDS) from the campaign unless Karadzic quits as party leader.
<p>
<b>Aleksa Buha</b>, the Bosnian Serb foreign minister, dismissed Frowick's warning. "If the SDS is excluded, then there won't be any elections in the Serb Republic," he told a rally of Serbs celebrating the sixth anniversary of the party's founding. Western concern with Bosnia's slide towards formal partition was highlighted with the disclosure that the U.S. architect of Dayton was returning to seek Karadzic's ouster.
<p>
<img src="holbrooke_90.gif" width=102 height=115 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Richard Holbrooke" align=left border=0><b>Richard Holbrooke</b>, who returned to business after negotiating Dayton as U.S. assistant secretary of state, will come back to the region on Monday at the behest of President Bill Clinton, the New York Times reported. He will lean on Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic to depose Karadzic and Bosnian Serb army commander General Ratko Mladic, also indicted for genocide and crimes against humanity.
<p>
The U.N. tribunal issued international arrest warrants for the two last week, exactly one year after Serb forces captured Srebrenica and massacred thousands of fleeing Moslems.</td>
</table>


<br><br>
