<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Srebrenica UN war crimes tribunal Ton Karremans Dutch peacekeepers
July 11, 1995">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Tribunal Hears how UN Abandoned Srebrenica</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Tribunal Hears How<br> 
U.N. Troops Abandoned<br> 
Srebrenica Victims</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<b>By Andrew Kelly</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="sreb_escapees2.gif" width=262 height=203 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Escapees from Srebrenica" align=left border=0>
THE HAGUE, July 4 (Reuter) - The U.N. and NATO failed to provide vital logistic and military support to U.N. peacekeepers during last year's Bosnian Serb assault on Srebrenica, a Dutch colonel told the Yugoslavia war crimes tribunal on Thursday.
<p>
"We didn't get any support at all," said Colonel Ton Karremans, former commander of the 400 Dutch peacekeepers assigned to protect the Moslem "safe haven" in eastern Bosnia. He was testifying at hearings in the case of Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his military commander General Ratko Mladic who are accused of the genocide of thousands of Moslems after Srebrenica fell to the Bosnian Serbs in July 1995.
<p>
Karremans said a long Serb blockade prior to the attack had left the lightly armed Dutch battalion desperately short of food and fuel but that requests for fresh supplies went unheeded.
<p>
He said he had first requested NATO air strikes when Mladic's troops began their assault on July 6 but that the request was not granted until July 11 when Srebrenica fell. "Everybody knows that the air strikes or close air support was too late and too little," he said.
<p>
Karremans said Mladic had threatened to kill 30 Dutch hostages and shell the Dutch base where thousands of terrified Moslems had fled unless the air strikes ended immediately. Over the next three days, Mladic dictated terms for the evacuation of some 25,000 refugees, thwarting the Dutch peacekeepers' attempt to monitor the process, Karremans said.
<p>
Karremans said his troops had reported the summary execution of nine people by Serb troops, but his evidence did not touch on the mass killings which prosecutors have described.
<p>
The indictment against Karadzic and Mladic says that thousands of Moslem men were rounded up in Srebrenica, taken to remote locations and summarily executed. It charges them with sharing overall responsibility for the killings. Both men remain at large in the Serb-controlled area of Bosnia and have not been represented at this week's hearings.
<p>
The so-called Rule 61 hearings do not amount to a trial in absentia -- forbidden under the tribunal's statute -- but are intended to create a forum for prosecutors to present evidence and call witnesses against accused persons who remain free.
<p>
Created by the U.N. Security Council in May 1993, the tribunal is the first body of its kind since the Nuremberg and Tokyo war crimes trials after World War Two. So far it has indicted 75 men, mainly Serbs, and holds seven of the accused at its cells in The Hague.</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
