Srebrenica Royal Dutch Marines ">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Dutch Bare Scars over Srebrenica</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Dutch Bare Scars over<br>
Role in Srebrenica</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<b>By Jennifer Scott</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="sreb_dutch.gif" width=262 height=187
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Royal Dutch Troops, 1995" align=left border=0>
AMSTERDAM, July 11 (Reuter) - The thousands of Moslems believed killed after the fall of Srebrenica weigh heavily on the Netherlands' conscience one year after Dutch peacekeepers failed to stop Bosnian Serb forces seizing the U.N. "safe area." It's hard to escape constant reminders of the slaughter.
<p>
Television images of skeletons uncovered in mass graves near the former Moslem enclave have fed the guilt and Dutch media re-appraise the macabre events of last July whenever new evidence comes to light. Experts say the recriminations have escalated in the past year as the full magnitude of the catastrophe has been realised. The guilt will only deepen as more questions are asked and evidence uncovered.
<p>
"The guilt for Srebrenica has always been taken by the Dutch," said Gert Denooy, military researcher at the Clingendael Research Institute for International Relations in The Hague. "There's a lot of soul searching going on to the extent they're not looking at their present role in Yugoslavia any more. There's a kind of paralysis."
<p>
Several hundred Bosnian refugees and Dutch sympathisers marched in silence through the streets of The Hague on Thursday to commemorate the estimated 6,000 Moslem men and boys missing and believed killed after Bosnian Serbs overran Srebrenica. The Moslems were alleged to have been killed by forces under the control of Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his military commander Ratko Mladic. The marchers planned to lay a wreath of white lilies, the national symbol of Bosnia, at a war memorial in the city.
<p>
"We will honour the memory of the murdered of Srebrenica and all the other victims of ethnic cleansing in former Yugoslavia," a spokesman for Bosnian-Dutch lobby group Stari Most said. The silent parade, setting off from the U.N. war crimes tribunal, coincides with proceedings against Karadzic and Mladic at which the tribunal is expected to reconfirm indictments against them and issue international arrest warrants.
<p>
A Dutch government report concluded last October that the Moslem enclave had fallen after a failure of U.N. policy in Bosnia with lightly-armed Dutch "blue-helmets" not to blame. But despite the exoneration, doubts linger as to whether the Dutch military did enough to prevent the huge loss of life. "As a group, (the Dutch peacekeeping force) did not distinguish itself heroically," said Algemeen Dagblad, the second biggest-selling Dutch newspaper, in an editorial on Thursday. "The humiliation that the blue-helmets suffered at the hands of the Bosnian Serbs will haunt them for a long time."
<p>
In a nation still scarred by the mass deportation of Dutch Jews during the World War Two, the fall of Srebrenica is another thorny issue to prick the Dutch conscience. "This will stay as a black mark on the list of Dutch ventures in international politics," said Denooy.
<p>
"But that's a trait of the way guilt and recrimination works within the Dutch system. It's the Christian, Protestant
way of looking at things, of living up to morals and values." But it is Dutch Defence Minister Joris Voorhoeve who has perhaps been dogged most by the tragedy of Srebrenica. "Voorhoeve has been constantly followed by the monster of
Srebrenica. It keeps kicking in the door when he tries to shut it out," said Denooy.
<p>
"He's trying to close the book on the affair, but I don't think he'll succeed."</td>
</table>


