<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Radovan Karadzic Ratko Mladic Srebrnica mass graves Cerska
Phsycians for Human Rights William Haglund">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Excavation Begins at Srebrenica Mass Grave</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Excavation Begins at<br>
Srebrenica Mass Grave</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=3><b>
‘We will concentrate on previously-visited sites,<br> 
using heavy equipment, labourers, forensic scientists<br>
and anthropologists. During the excavation process,<br> 
we will expose the entire grave.’</b><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>—John Gerns, U.S. Pathologist<br>
<font size=2>
<p>

<b>By Mark Heinrich</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="sreb_77.gif" width=262 height=202
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Aerial Probe of Srebrenica Grave Sites" align=left border=0>
CERSKA, Bosnia (Reuter) - War crimes investigators began a three-month quest Sunday to unearth mass graves of victims of ethnic massacres in Bosnia and Croatia, starting with Muslims killed in the Bosnian Serb conquest of Srebrenica. 
<p>
A multinational team sent by the International Criminal Tribunal on former Yugoslavia sealed off their first excavation site, an embankment off a dirt road on a wooded hill 35 km (21 miles) west of Srebrenica in eastern Bosnia.
<p>
After a Norwegian mine-clearing unit checked for unexploded ordnance or booby traps, finding none, workers moved in to remove brambles and underbrush to prepare for several days of digging starting Monday. U.S. troops in NATO's Bosnia peace force provided a security net of Bradley combat vehicles and Humvee jeeps mounted with machine-guns to deter possible attempts by local Serbs keen to thwart war crimes prosecutions.
<p>
The U.N. tribunal in The Hague has indicted separatist Serb army commander General Ratko Mladic and wartime political chief Radovan Karadzic for genocide and crimes against humanity. Both remain at large seven months after the Dayton peace treaty that split into Serb and Croat-Muslim halves and exactly a year after the bloodbath at Srebrenica which may have been Europe's worst atrocity since the Nazi Holocaust.
<p>
At least 3,000, and possibly as many as 8,000, mostly unarmed Muslim males are believed to have been killed after capture or killed in ambushes as Serb forces overran Srebrenica, a supposed U.N.-protected "safe area."
<p>
The tribunal's investigators are returing to suspected mass grave sites after several "test trenches" were dug by hand in preliminary inspections earlier this year. They then found several bodies twisted over each other and at least two had their arms tied behind their backs, hardening suspicions of mass graves containing scores, hundreds or possibily even thousands of victims.
<p>
This time, the investigators will be disinterring entire sites with the help of earth-moving machines, including a seven-ton backhoe, and local Serbs recruited as laborers equipped with shovels and wheelbarrows. "During the excavation process, we will expose entire graves. We will concentrate on previously visited sites," said John Gerns, a leading U.S. pathologist on the team.
<p>
He said the team, including forensic anthropologists, odontologists, geneticists and ballistics experts, would be at the iirst site in Cerkka for several days. Excavated human remains will be packed into refrigerated trucks and taken to a secure morgue where experts will try to identify them, ascertain their injuries and pinpoint the cause and date of death. Problems complicating identification include a lack of medical and dental records as well as cooperation by Serbs who have denounced the tribunal as a kangaroo court biased against their people.
<p>
Indications that some grave sites may have been tampered with to destroy evidence have lent impetus to the tribunal's probe. It expected to excavate at least a half dozen sites in the wooded hills of the Drina Valley near Srebrenica. It also planned to uncover a total of 20 sites over the next three months, some of them elsewhere in Bosnia and Croatia and unconnected with Srebrenica.
<p>
All sites were pinpointed either by survivors, witnesses or satellite photographs provided by the United States to the U.N. Security Council late last year. The Srebrenica sites include a meadow at Nova Kasaba that U.S. officials say may contain up to 2 ,700 bodies, a reservoir spillway near Zvornik and a field at Pilica where a former Serb soldier held by the tribunal has admitted involvement in hundreds of killings in a single day.
</td>
</table>


<br><br>
