">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Smith Not Being Forced from Bosnia</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=5><b>
Pentagon Insists Leighton Smith<br>
Isn’t being Forced from Bosnia</b>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=2><b>
Some in Europe have criticized him for not capturing<br>
suspected war criminals. But stories of disagreements<br>
with other allied commanders are said to be 'not true.'</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<font size=2><img src="lsmith_lg.gif" width=160 height=200 align=left vspace=3 alt="Admiral Leighton Smith">
WASHINGTON, June 11 (AP) — The U.S. admiral in charge of NATO’s peacekeeping force in Bosnia will leave his post in July but is not being forced out, a Pentagon spokesman said Tuesday. 
<p>
Kenneth Bacon said the exact date of departure for Adm. Leighton Smith Jr. will depend on when his chosen successor, Vice Adm. Joseph Lopez, is confirmed by the Senate. Until now officials had been less precise, saying only that he would leave this summer.
<p>
The NATO mission in Bosnia is due to end in December.
<p>
Smith, a 1962 graduate of the Naval Academy, will retire within two months of leaving his post. Bacon praised him for a "magnificent job" in Bosnia. Smith has been criticized by some, particularly in Europe, who believe the allied troops should take a more aggressive role in finding and arresting suspected war criminals.
<p>
Bacon decried what he called "highly unfortunate and inaccurate stories" about Smith leaving because of disagreements with other allied commanders. "Those stories are not true. They are flat wrong," Bacon said.
<p>
Smith, whose two-year tour as commander of U.S. Naval Forces Europe and commander of Allied Forces Southern Europe was up in April, volunteered to leave in order to make room for others below him to be promoted in rank and position, Bacon said.
<p>
From his NATO post in Naples, Italy, Smith ran the allied bombing campaign against the Bosnian Serbs last August and September that many credit with creating the conditions which led to the Dayton accord ending the Bosnian war in November.</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<img src="background.gif" alt="To learn more..." align=bottom border=0><br>
