Radovan Karadzic Ratko Mladic UN NATO IFOR Balkan">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: 2 Killed, 21 Injured when Bus Hits Anti-Tank Mine</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
2 Killed, 21 Injured As<br>
Bus Hits Anti-Tank Mine</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<font size=2>
SARAJEVO, July 2 (Reuter) - Two people were killed and 21 injured when a bus carrying civilians hit an anti-tank mine in northwest Bosnia, highlighting the acute mine problem in the war-ravaged country, NATO said on Tuesday.
<p>
"The incident happened on Monday afternoon seven km (four miles) south of Sipovo," Major Tom Moyer, spokesman for the NATO-led peace implementation force (IFOR) in Sarajevo, told Reuters. He said the bus, "with probably Serb civilians in it," hit an anti-tank mine while entering a marked mine field. He said 10 of the injured were in a very serious condition.
<p>
Moyer said the IFOR British unit in charge of the area reacted immediately and sent a field ambulance unit and an explosive ordnance disposal team. Before being able to help the casualties, the British troops had to clear the area of other mines, he said.
<p>
Moyer said the wounded were first treated in an IFOR hospital and later taken to the civilian hospital in Sipovo.
<p>
Experts estimate there could be up to three million mines strewn across Bosnia, now being cleared mostly by IFOR and by local forces. Donor countries participating in Bosnia's post-war reconstruction have allocated millions of dollars for clearing mines, a recognition of the huge obstacle these constitute to a restoration of normality after the 43-month war in the former Yugoslav republic.</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<img src="background.gif" alt="To learn more..." align=bottom border=0><br>
Berserkistan, May 4 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="geneva_a.html">U.S. Welcomes New Landmine Agreement</a><br> 
Berserkistan, Apr 21 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="mine_ban.html">Landmine Talks Seen Setting New Rules, No Ban</a><br>
<a href="http://www.cdi.org/issues/boslm.html">Landmine Hazards in Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia</a><br>
<a href="http://www.linder.com/berserk/mines.html">Landmine Awareness & Survival Techniques</a> from Berserkistan <br>
<a href="http://www.counterterrorism.com/mines.htm">The Mine Awareness Training Course</a><br>
<a href="http://tlingit.elmail.co.uk:2000/reference/briefs/landmines.html">The Landmine Control Programme: A
Humanitarian Initiative</a><br>
<a href="http://www.apk.net/ucc/global/landmine.htm">Global Landmine Crisis</a> Global Ministries</a><br>
