<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia
bombs Livno international police monitors Bugojno Ejup Ganic">


<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Bombings Fuel Fears of Increasing Nationalist Violence in Bosnia</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Bombings Fuel Fears of<br>
Increasing Nationalist
Violence in Bosnia</b>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=3><b>
The incidents, which caused no injuries,<br> 
followed tit-for-tat firebombings of Moslem<br>  
and Croat religious and cultural sites</b><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<p>
<b>By Mark Heinrich</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="m_bombs_729.gif" width=214 height=204 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="MAP: Recent Bombings" align=left border=0>
SARAJEVO, July 29 (Reuter) - Two bombs destroyed vehicles
owned by Moslems in Croat-controlled western Bosnia over the
weekend in a worrying escalation of nationalist violence, the
U.N. said on Monday.
<p>
The incidents, which caused no injuries, followed
tit-for-tat firebombings of Moslem and Croat religious and
cultural sites and emphasised the fragility of Bosnia's
Moslem-Croat post-war federation.
<p>
U.N. spokesman Alex Ivanko said a bomb outside a
Moslem-owned home used by international police monitors in the
town of Livno blew up early on Sunday, destroying a truck belong
to the Moslem.
Five hours later, a bomb exploded beneath a car belonging to
the Livno branch of a Moslem humanitarian agency.
<p>
Ivanko expressed concern that the Bosnian Croat police had
taken six hours to respond to the first incident.
He said communal violence seemed to be escalating at a time
of political stalemate between Moslems and Croats in the divided
city of Mostar following disputed municipal elections.
<p>
Countrywide elections are due in Bosnia in September.
<p>
Last week, a bomb seriously damaged a Croat Catholic church
in the central Moslem-controlled town of Bugojno. The bombing
followed arson attacks on four other churches, and the
fire-bombing of a mosque in Croat-controlled Prozor.
<p>
Ejup Ganic, Moslem vice-president in the Sarajevo
government, said the security situation for remaining minority
Moslems in the Livno area had worsened since the European Union
validated the Moslems' electoral victory in Mostar.
A number of Moslem houses in Livno and nearby Glamoc had
been mined recently while two Moslem cars, buildings on a Moslem
farm and a Moslem shop had been blown up, a statement issued by
Ganic's office said.
It said a bomb was also found in another Moslem house in the
village of Kablici, outside Livno.
<p>
Separatist minority Croats and the Bosnian government waged
war in 1993-94 before U.S. pressure pushed them into a loose
federation. But the entity remains split into a Croat-held west
and Moslem-dominated centre. Serbs hold east and north Bosnia.
<p>
Bosnian Croat leader Kresimir Zubak accused the Bosnian
government over the weekend of orchestrating ethnic violence
behind a mask of support for a united, multi-cultural Bosnia.
<p>
A U.N. official, who asked not be named, criticised Zubak's
remarks as "inflammatory and unhelpful" and said a comment by
Bosnian Moslem President Alija Izetbegovic, warning of a new
threat of war with Croats, was ill-considered as well.
</td></table>


