<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Mass graves Cerska William Haglund Srebrenica victims Goran Neskovic">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Bosnian Serb Official Confronts Dead at Cerska</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Bosnian Serb Official<br>
Confronts Dead at Cerska</b>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=3><b>
The Serb official listened without any outward sign of emotion as Haglund described how the victims were lined up on an embankment and shot at close range. "There were a lot of massacres in this area," he said.</b><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<p><B>From wire service reports</b><p>
<font size=2>
<img src="dead4_lg.gif" width=262 height=228 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Srebrenica victim at Cerska" align=left border=0>
CERSKA, Bosnia, July 18 (AP) -- The first Bosnian Serb official to visit a mass grave being exhumed by war crimes investigators listened impassively Thursday to a description of how Bosnian Serb forces summarily executed Muslim civilians.
<p>
"These people were lined up on this side of the road and then shot," the forensic team leader, William D. Haglund, told Goran Neskovic, the deputy justice minister of the Bosnian Serb republic. "Everyone we’ve found so far was wearing civilian clothing."
<p>
Investigators digging at the mass grave in Cerska, 17 miles northwest of Srebrenica, have disputed Serb assertions that most of the dead were soldiers shot while fighting. They say the 134 victims uncovered so far had their hands wired behind their backs and were shot after being lined up atop an embankment.
<p>
Nearly 7,000 residents of Srebrenica are missing and feared dead a year after Bosnian Serbs overran the Muslim enclave in eastern Bosnia. Testimony of survivors and other evidence suggests that most were massacred by the Bosnian Serbs -- the war’s worst atrocity. The Cerska dig is being conducted by the U.N. war crimes tribunal, which has indicted Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and Gen. Ratko Mladic, his military commander, for their alleged roles in the Srebrenica massacre.
<p>
Reporters were kept away from Thursday’s conversation between Neskovic and Haglund, but were still able to overhear Haglund explaining how the victims died. Haglund said his team had removed 134 sets of human remains after more than two weeks of digging at the Cerska site and expected to find a total of about 150 victims.
<p>
<img src="dead7.gif" width=262 height=234
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Forensics Team members at Cerska" align=left border=0>
<b>Neskovic listened without any outward sign of emotion</b> as Haglund described how the victims were lined up on an embankment and shot at close range, with the spent cartridges scattered among their bodies. 
<p>
"There were a lot of massacres in this area," Neskovic responded, referring to the Bosnian Serbs’ assertion that any massacres of Muslims in the region were to avenge the slayings of hundreds of Serb villagers by Muslim troops.
<p>
Serb authorities earlier maintained that all bodies found around Srebrenica were of soldiers killed in battle. This time they told ICTY the Moslems were killed in revenge for their previous massacre of Serbs around Srebrenica. But Bill Stuebner, acting head of ICTY office in the Bosnian capital Sarajevo, dismissed the argument.
<p>
"Revenge is never a justification," Stuebner said. "We know there were a lot of ugly things that happened here and the Tribunal is looking into all those things...  But criminals are criminals and victims are victims."
<p>
Haglund said the team would probably pull out the last remains Thursday and remove them Friday to an undisclosed site on territory held by the Muslim-Croat federation for examination and identification. The team plans to begin working Sunday at nearby Nova Kasaba -- in an area identified last year by U.S. spy satellite photographs as possibly containing as many as 2,700 bodies of Srebrenica victims, investigators said. 
<p>
"We will probably finish here today. We got 16 more bodies plus remainders and it's going to take us to about 150 (bodies)," team leader William Haglund told reporters. The team of experts, sent by the international war crimes tribunal on former Yugoslavia (ICTY), started excavating the first of several suspected mass tombs near the former Moslem enclave of Srebrenica 11 days ago.
<p>
On Tuesday and Wednesday, investigators uncovered 30 bodies of Muslim victims in Zerovanj, 15½ miles northwest of Sarajevo, many with their hands tied. In the northwestern village of Kamen, Serbs spent a second day Wednesday exhuming bodies of their soldiers and civilians from a mass grave in Muslim-Croat federation territory. Investigators said the site, and two others nearby, could yield as many as 120 bodies. 
</td>
</table>


