Radovan Karadzic Ratko Mladic UN NATO IFOR Balkan">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Kosovo Albanian Leader in Bonn for Talks</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Kosovo Albanian Leader<br>
in Bonn for Talks</b>
<font size=4>
<p>
<b>‘Kosovo Albanians have declared their willingness to open negotiations with Belgrade. Belgrade should now take up this offer’</b><br>
<font size=2>
—German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="kinkel.gif" width=136 height=191 
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Klaus Kinkel" align=left border=0>
BONN, July 11 (Reuter) - German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel met a leader of the ethnic Albanian community in the Serbian province of Kosovo on Thursday and called on Belgrade to open talks with the group on human rights. "The human rights and minority rights of Albanians in Kosovo cannot remain overshadowed by the resolution of problems in Bosnia-Herzegovina," Kinkel said after meeting Ibrahim Rugova, head of the Democratic League of Kosovo (DLK), in Bonn.
<p>
"Kosovo Albanians have declared their willingness to open negotiations with Belgrade. Belgrade should now take up this offer," he said in a statement, adding Serbia's ties with the European Union depended on settling Kosovo's problems. Rugova has in the past emphasised his support for peaceful resistance to Serbian rule in the predominantly Albanian province at the south end of rump Yugoslavia.
<p>
The foreign ministry statement said Kinkel and Rugova discussed Kosovo's current situation, "which remains absolutely unsatisfactory and marked by fear and discrimination against the Albanian majority." It said Germany's ties with Belgrade would be affected by how fully Belgrade respects human and minority rights in the region and how it grants Kosovo "a high degree of autonomy.''
<p>
"Belgrade must know that full integration in the community of nations and access to long-term financial aid and close co-operation with the European Unjon is a two-way street in regard to Kosovo," it added.  Concerned about its ethnic kin, Albania has demanded the withdrawal of Serbian military police from Kosovo and immediate three-party talks between Serbia, Kosovo and Albania.
<p>
Yugoslav and Serbian authorities insist Kosovo is an internal problem and have refused offers of foreign mediation to end sporadic violence there. Belgrade argues Kosovo Albanians want to secede and join neighbouring Albania. Serbia rescinded the province's 15-year old autonomy status in 1989.

</td>
</table>


