"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Radovan Karadzic Ratko Mladic Naser Oric Srebrenica July 11, 1995 safe area Ejup Ganic">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Moslem Commander Vows to Regain Srebrenica</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Moslem Commander Vows<br>
to Regain Srebrenica</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<b>By Samir Arnaut</b>
<p>
<font size=2>
<img src="sreb_city2.gif" width=261 height=207
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Srebrenica" align=left border=0>
TUZLA, Bosnia, July 13 (Reuter) - The former commander of Moslem Srebrenica's military garrison has publicly vowed to regain the "safe area" which fell to separatist Serbs a year ago, despite world promises of protection. 
<p>
"We will go back," even if blood had to be shed again, Naser Oric told an emotional rally on Friday of 40,000 to 50,000 Bosnian Moslem refugees from the town in eastern Bosnia.
<p>
The rally was staged as war crimes investigators unearthed a mass grave near Srebrenica believed to contain missing Moslems. "We want Srebrenica where our sons are," and "We want to go back," people cried, as several women fainted, weeping. Men threw stones and apples and shouted abuse at several speakers. Separatist Serb forces overran the eastern Bosnian town of Srebrenica on July 11, 1995, expelled some 30,000 Moslem women, children and elderly and U.N. war-crimes investigators say, massacred between 3,000 and 8,000 unarmed men in flight. Authorities say this was the worst atrocity in Europe since World War Two.
<p>
A year on from Srebrenica's fall, the international war crimes tribunal in The Hague issued arrest warrants for the
Serbs' political leader Radovan Karadzic and his military commander Ratko Mladic, both accused of genocide. The bloodbath that overwhelmed U.N. troops mandated to "protect" the Bosnian government enclave led to NATO bombing raids which crippled the Serb war machine and yielded the Dayton peace treaty on Bosnia in December.
<p>
U.N. investigators, hampered by slow international bureaucracy, are only now starting to exhume mass graves identified by massacre survivors or spy satellite photos as long ago as August 1995.
<p>
<img src="sreb_city.gif" width=262 height=219
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Srebrenica" align=left border=0>
Experts say remains of civilians found in a mass grave near Srebrenica bear evidence they were massacred, not killed in battle as Bosnian Serb officials claim. 
<p>
"People in blue helmets (the U.N.) took away from us the few arms we had. And we believed in a better tomorrow... the U.N. handed us over to the butcher, it wasn't Mladic who captured us," said Fahrudin Salihovic, president of the Srebrenica municipality.
<p>
"(U.N. Secretary General Boutros) Boutros Ghali is responsible for the crimes. Srebrenica will never forgive him.
That was a treason," said Ejup Ganic, a member of the Bosnian presidency and a vice-president of the Moslem-Croat federation. Women, children and aged who survived the Srebrenica massacre now live in extreme poverty around Tuzla, and have next to no hope of returning home.
<p>
Many live in dreary collection centres where the food is slop and people sleep crammed in rooms. Most survive on charity. Srebrenica, 75 km (45 miles) southeast of Tuzla, is now a haven for Serb refugees from Bosnian federal territory. Srebrenica women refugees association in Tuzla claim some of the 6,000 men initially listed as missing are still held in Serb prisons, and demand international action to free them.
<p>
The rally, organised by the Bosnian government, assembled people from all over Bosnia, who came to Tuzla in buses. Many share the same fate as the Srebrenica refugees, as nationalists on all sides prevent people from returning home, despite commitments they made under the Dayton peace treaty.
<p>
"We should not raise problems because of our dead today. (We should) stay calm and dignified," Oric said."But we must and we will go back... We won't let criminals get away with it wherever they may be." "The battle for Bosnia continues with all means until everyone returns to his (pre-war) home. Maybe blood will be spilt on this way, but we have to endure," Oric said.</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<img src="background.gif" alt="To learn more..." align=bottom border=0><br>
