</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Radovan Karadzic Ratko Mladic UN NATO IFOR Balkan">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Women of Srebrenica Starting Over</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Women of Srebrenica<br>
Find Themselves<br>
Starting Over</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<font size=4>
<b>‘For me, it’s too late, but for my oldest, Belma, I wish she 
could have education and be able to provide for herself.’</b><br>
<font size=2>—Mejra Alic, mother of three<br>
<p>
<a href="sreb_711.html"><img src="woman2.gif" width=262 height=200 border=0
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="Women at Tuzla Memorial Ceremony" align=left border=0></a>
TUZLA, July 13 (AP) -- They endured attacks and expulsions, saw their husbands and sons being hauled away. But it is the prospect of starting over that many women of Srebrenica find too much to bear. 
<p>
About 7,000 Muslim men disappeared when Serbs overran the U.N.-protected enclave in eastern Bosnia a year ago. Most of the women were evacuated and, as refugees, lived on the hope that somehow, somewhere, their men might still be alive.
<p>
But as war crimes investigators began unearthing mass graves this past week, the women braced for the painful truth, and an unavoidable question: what now? Coming from a tradition in which they are given little education and are provided for by men, many have no idea how to go on.
<p>
"For me, it’s too late," said Mejra Alic, a frail mother of three who looks much older than her 30 years. "But for my oldest, Belma, I wish she could have education and be able to provide for herself." Belma is 11. Like others, Alic and her children fled to Tuzla, a government-held city about 45 miles northwest of Srebrenica. They had depended on her husband, Behadel, an auto mechanic, who disappeared in the fall of Srebrenica. For the last year, they have lived on meager aid in a room provided by a host family whose patience is growing thin. Asked about her plans, Alic shrugged: "My life is over anyway."
<p>
Overwhelmed by the tragedy, few of the women have accepted that their prospects of returning to Srebrenica -- now being resettled by Serb refugees from elsewhere in Bosnia -- are virtually nil. Efforts to teach them marketable skills are rare. Most of them, true to tradition, are reluctant to seek support outside the family, and the war has broken up the extended-family networks that might have stepped in.
<p>
<img src="srebvic_m.gif" width=252 height=202 hspace=0 vspace=3 align=left 
border=0 alt="About 7,000 Muslim men are believed dead">
"The women... are not well organized, they are not well educated, and they do not have a clear, long-term objective," said Randolph Ryan, spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Tuzla. "The question is: do they focus only on trying to go home, or do they decide to start rebuilding their lives?"  
<p>
An international effort to help them is under way. On Thursday, several thousand women gathered at a Tuzla sports hall to meet a foreign delegation led by Queen Noor of Jordan, U.S. Ambassador to Austria Swanee Hunt and European Union Human Affairs Commissioner Emma Bonino.
<p>
"We are going to help these women start businesses, help them start over again," said Hunt, who helped collect several million dollars to get them started. Bonino delivered the most direct message. "You must never forget," she told them. "And you must look ahead into the future."
<p>
But only the children and very young women appeared able to break out of a deadening combination of tragedy-induced lethargy and tradition. "Oh my honey, what could I do with this fancy box?" said Zahrija Zafirovic, 30, when the delegation presented the women with personal computers. "I only know how to cook."
<p>
Mina Ramic, however, was undeterred. A lively young woman of 18, she became head of the family when her mother "could not shake off" what happened. Ramic now supports her mother and two younger sisters by working at the local textile factory, and studies at a trade school in her free time. She was only sent to elementary school by her parents. Her sister Selma is the first girl in the family to attend high school. 
<p>
"Had we still been living at home, Selma would probably not go to school, and I would probably be looking for a husband," Ramic said. "But everything has changed. We have to take care of ourselves now."
</td>
</table>


<br><br>
