<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Dario Kordic war crimes tribunal Croatia Zagreb Split Zlatko Aleksovski">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Croatia to Surrender First War Crime Suspect</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Croatia to Surrender<br>
Zlatko Aleksovski,<br>
First War Crime Suspect</b>
<font size=2>
<p>
<font size=4>
<b>Meantime, top Croat suspect is found<br> 
living confortably in Zagreb</b><br>
<p>

<font size=2>
<blockquote><font size=2>
<font color="#A62A2A"><b>SUSPECT PROFILE</b>
<hr size=1 align=left>
<font color="#454545"><b>Zlatko Alekosovski worked in a prison in Zenica from 23 February 1987 until receiving an administrative post at prison facilities in Kaonik, near Busovac, around 29 January 1993. 
<p>
He was the warden of the prison Kaonik, where he held meetings with representatives of the International Red Cross and inspectors from the European Union's mission. Zlatko Aleksovski allowed illegal interrogations of imprisoned individuals as well the practice of using prisoners for slave labor and as human shields.</b><p> 
<font size=2>—<a href="http://www.amber.ucsf.edu/homes/ross/public_html/bosnia_/crocrim3.txt"><b>Globus</b></a> Number 259 from 24 November, 1995
</blockquote><br>
<font size=2>
<b>By Davor Huic</b>
<p>
ZAGREB, July 10 (Reuter) - Croatian authorities will hand over a Bosnian Croat war crimes suspect to a U.N. criminal tribunal, in the country's first case of extradition to the international body, newspapers said on Wednesday. At the same time, a leading political weekly reported that the tribunal's number one Croat suspect, former Bosnian Croat leader Dario Kordic, remained living in the centre of Zagreb with impunity. The Split county court ruled on Tuesday that it would comply with the tribunal's request to turn over Zlatko Aleksovski to its custody, Slobodna Dalmacija daily and other media said.
<p>
It is the first time that Croatia acted on its three-month old special law on cooperation with the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague as required by the Dayton peace agreement. Court officials were not immediately available to confirm the reports. Aleskovski, 36, one of six Bosnian Croats accused of the ethnic cleansing of Moslems in Bosnian central Lasva valley, was arrested in June in Split and has been held in custody ever since.
<p>
<img src="m_lasva.gif" width=214 height=204 
align=left vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="MAP: Lasva Valley">
He was charged with grave breaches of laws or customs of war, in particular for unlawful treatment of Moslem detainees while he was the commander of several prison camps. Bosnian Moslems and Croats fought a bitter 10-month war in 1993 overshadowed by the central Serb-Moslem conflict. The exact date of Aleskovski's extradition could not be specified, since under the law he has a right to appeal to a higher court within eight days.
<p>
Under strong pressure from abroad, senior Croatian officials said all the indictees found on Croatian soil would be arrested and turned over to the Hague tribunal. The Council of Europe has made Croatia's admittance conditional upon its compliance with the U.N. war crimes court.
<p>
It is believed that many of the suspects are at large in Bosnia, but Globus weekly brought up new evidence that the man who tops the tribunal's list of most wanted Croat suspects live in the centre of Zagreb. It published pictures of Kordic in white shirt and sneakers, taken allegedly on Monday, in front of his apartment in Zagreb's central Tresnjevka district. The weekly said Kordic lived on the fourth floor with no name on the door, in a new-built block owned by the defence ministry, where he moved immediately after he had been indicted. Globus quoted a list of state officials, including the police, the county court and foreign and interior ministries, who refused to comment on Kordic's whereabouts.
<p>
When indicted in November 1995, Kordic was the head of the Bosnian wing of the Croatian ruling party, HDZ (Croatian
Democratic Union). The Hague tribunal charged him with crimes against humanity committed against the Moslems in the Lasva valley, where he was the political and military leader. Kordic's right hand at the time, general Tihomir Blaskic, handed himself over voluntarily to the Tribunal in April. The tribunal has so far indicted 75 men, 18 of them Croats, and holds seven in its Hague cells.</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<img src="background.gif" alt="To learn more..." align=bottom border=0><br>
