<HTML>
<META Name="keywords" Content=
"Bosnia Herzegovina Serbia Croatia Former Yugoslavia 
Radovan Karadzic Ratko Mladic UN NATO IFOR Balkan">

<HEAD>
<title>BERSERKISTAN IN BOSNIA: Joint Croat-Serb Police Begin Patrolling Slavonia</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#454545" link="#A62A2A" vlink="#B87333">

<BODY>
<blockquote>
<img src="flat280.gif" width=280 height=119 
align=bottom vspace=0 hspace=0 alt="BERSERKISTAN">
<br>
<hr size=1 align=left>

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=15>
<TD WIDTH=88 valign=top align=right>
<font size=1>
<img src="navigator.gif" USEMAP="#navigator" 
width=80 height=256 alt="Berserkistan Navigator" hspace=0 
vspace=2 align=bottom border=0></td>

<TD valign=top align=left>
<FONT SIZE=6><b>
Joint Croat-Serb Police<br>
Begin Patrolling Slavonia</b>
<font size=2><p>
<img src="m_slavonia.gif" width=262 height=207
vspace=5 hspace=0 alt="MAP: Slavonia" align=left border=0>
ZAGREB, July 1 (Reuter) - Joint Croatian-Serb police under U.N. administration on Monday began patrolling Eastern Slavonia, the last enclave in Croatia held by rebel Serbs, in a sign the area could make a peaceful return to Zagreb's rule. 
<p>
A U.N. spokesman in Vukovar, the biggest town of the oil-rich, fertile enclave bordering Serbia proper, told Reuters the police force would eventually number up to 1,300.
<p>
It was the first time Croats and Serbs had policed the area together since May 1991, when the first ethnic fighting broke out in Borovo Selo, near Vukovar.
<p>
Croatian state radio quoted the U.N. administrator for the region, retired U.S. General Jacques Klein who attended an inauguration ceremony on a former front line, as saying patrols formally started to operate on Monday. "The police will be wearing neutral uniforms, neither Croat nor Serb, and will enforce law and order in the region," the spokesman said. But they would be paid from funds provided by the Croatian government, he added.
<p>
Minority Serbs rebelled against Croatia's independence drive from former Yugoslavia in 1991, proclaimed their own state and expelled thousands of non-Serbs from the territory they controlled. Croatian troops stormed three Serb separatist enclaves last summer, sending almost 200,000 Serbs fleeing for safety to Serbia and Bosnia.
<p>
Agreement on Eastern Slavonia was reached last December on the fringes of the Dayton peace talks for Bosnia. The accord envisages the region's peaceful reversion to Zagreb's rule, with the help of the U.N. administration and some 5,000 peacekeepers.
<p>
After the opening of a vital motorway, restoration of telephone and transport communications, the area's demilitarisation, monitored by the U.N., was completed on June 21.
<p>
More than 1,000 Croat and Serb policemen have finished special training courses held in the region or in nearby Hungary. The composition of the force is supposed to reflect the area's pre-war ethnic composition, the spokesman said.
</td>
</table>


<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<img src="background.gif" alt="To learn more..." align=bottom border=0><br>
Berserkistan, June 28 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="croatia_628.html">Croatia Excludes 811 from from Serb Amnesty Law</a><br>
Berserkistan, June 28 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="croatia_628a.html">Boutros-Ghali Calls for More UN Troops in Eastern Slavonia</a><br>
Berserkistan, June 12 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="cro_commo_612.html">Phone Service Restored to Eastern Slavonia</a><br> 
Berserkistan, May 7 <b>&#183;</b> <a href="yugo_cross.html">Team Berserkistan First Across Yugoslav Confrontation Line</a><br>
<p>
EASTERN SLAVONIA<br>
<a href="http://www.freenet.hamilton.on.ca/~ae987/Croatia/ecrohis.html">History of Eastern Croatia</a><br>
<a href="http://www.wideopen.igc.org/balkans/vukovar.html">VukoWar, Where War Struck Slavonia Hardest</a><br>
<a href="http://www.yugoslavia.com/Bulletin/95/9512/951211.htm">Basic Agreement on the District of Eastern Slavonia</a> As signed November, 1995 <br>


